PREDICTING DIABETES READMISSIONS¶

Task : Predict Hospital readmissions for diabetes patients. In this asssignment, I will make use of various machine learning models to predict hospital readmissions for diabetes patients.

Start Time : 12:45 AM

End Time : 2:30 AM

  8. Next Steps

Next, we will try to define a function which calculates the prevelance of population of diabetes patients that is likely to be readmitted.

In [8]:
def calc_prevalence(y_actual):
    return (sum(y_actual)/len(y_actual))
In [9]:
print('Prevalence:%.3f'%calc_prevalence(df['readmitted'].values))

Prevalence:0.112

As we can see, about 11% of the population is readmitted. (Pretty Unbalanced, right?)

After analyzing these columns, I have come up with the variables I want to use in my model and with the ones I want to drop.

II. Feature Extraction and Modifications¶

In my approach, I have not used techniques like PCA to reduce the size of features because there were not a very large size of columns. I preferred looking at each column manually to understand its importance and to not lose any column that could be valuable to my prediction.

As seen in our dataset, there are a lot missing values (?). Our first task in Feature Extraction should be replacing all these ? values with Nan.

In [12]:
# replace ? with nan
df = df.replace('?',np.nan)

Following is the list of features that I will not be using in my analysis and their reasons :

  1. encounter_id and patient_nbr : These are not useful variables in my model as they are just identfiers.
  2. examide and citoglipton : These variables have only 1 value so there is not much sense to use them in the model.
  3. diag1,diag2, diag3 : These variables have a lot of categorical values which we cannot determine the meaning of and will overcomplicate the model.

Choosing and defining our variables¶

Since there are a lot of variables, we can pick the top 10 and create a feature with 11 values. (Top 10 and an Other category).

In [19]:
top_10 = ['UNKNOWN','InternalMedicine','Emergency/Trauma',\
          'Family/GeneralPractice', 'Cardiology','Surgery-General' ,\
          'Nephrology','Orthopedics',\
          'Orthopedics-Reconstructive','Radiologist']
# make a new column with duplicated data
df['medical_spec_new'] = df['medical_specialty'].copy()
# replace all specialties not in top 10 with 'Other' category
df.loc[~df.medical_specialty.isin(top_10),'medical_spec_new'] = 'Other'

When we check the head of this dataframe, we can see our dummy variables. For eg; The Race column has been divided into various different columns such as race_Asian, race_Hispanic etc. and each of these dummy columns have binary values 0,1. This suggests that if a patient is Asian, the value will be 1 and otherwise it will be 0.

III. Treating Imbalanced Training Data¶

Since our data is already split into training and test set, I will skip that part and try to balance the training data to prevent bias.

In [34]:
##BALANCING TRAINING DATA
# Splitting the data into positive and negative 
rows_pos = df_data.readmitted == 1
df_train_pos = df_data.loc[rows_pos]
df_train_neg = df_data.loc[~rows_pos]

# merging the balanced data
df_train = pd.concat([df_train_pos, df_train_neg.sample(n = len(df_train_pos), random_state = 42)],axis = 0)

# shuffle the order of training samples 
df_train = df_train.sample(n = len(df_train), random_state = 42).reset_index(drop = True)

print('Train balanced prevalence(n = %d):%.3f'%(len(df_train), calc_prevalence(df_train.readmitted.values)))

Train balanced prevalence(n = 18172):0.500

Defining an Input Matrix X and Output Vector Y :

In [35]:
X_train = df_data[cols_to_use].values
y_train = df_data['readmitted'].values
In [36]:
print('Training shapes:',X_train.shape, y_train.shape)

Training shapes: (81414, 149) (81414,)

IV. Modeling¶

The classification techniques that I will use to train my dataset are K-Nearest Neighbours Classifier, Logistic Regression and Random Forest Classifier. Machine Learning models used in the healthcare field should be interpretable. The more complex a Machine Learning Model, the less interpretable it gets. In the healthcare field, these complex models are difficult to understand and might not always make sense. If you load the following code yyou will see a graph I referred to while coming up with the techniques to use in this particular model :

In [41]:
from IPython.display import Image 
from IPython.core.display import HTML 
Image(url= "https://miro.medium.com/max/1400/0*fvrBaILFAaCCsYHT")
Out[41]:

1. KNN Classifier¶

In [42]:
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
In [43]:
knn = KNeighborsClassifier(100)
knn.fit(X_train, y_train)
print('Train score: {:.4f}'.format(knn.score(X_train, y_train)))

Train score: 0.8884

2. Logistic Regression¶

In [44]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
In [45]:
lr=LogisticRegression(solver='liblinear',random_state = 0)
lr.fit(X_train_tf, y_train)
print('Train score: {:.4f}'.format(lr.score(X_train_tf, y_train)))

Train score: 0.8883

3. Random Forest¶

In [46]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
In [47]:
rf=RandomForestClassifier(max_depth = 6, random_state = 0, n_estimators=100)
rf.fit(X_train_tf, y_train)
print('Train score: {:.4f}'.format(rf.score(X_train_tf, y_train)))

Train score: 0.8884

As we can see, the train scores for all the models are similar. I will be using Logistic Regression to predict hospital readmissions for patients as this technique is widely used to predict binomial outcomes and can be used for cancer detection problems. It is the most relavent and least complicated.

Since there are a lot of variables, we can pick the top 10 and create a feature with 11 values. (Top 10 and an Other category).

In [59]:
top_10 = ['UNKNOWN','InternalMedicine','Emergency/Trauma',\
          'Family/GeneralPractice', 'Cardiology','Surgery-General' ,\
          'Nephrology','Orthopedics',\
          'Orthopedics-Reconstructive','Radiologist']
# make a new column with duplicated data
df1['medical_spec_new'] = df1['medical_specialty'].copy()
# replace all specialties not in top 10 with 'Other' category
df1.loc[~df1.medical_specialty.isin(top_10),'medical_spec_new'] = 'Other'

VI. Final Predictions on Test Set Using Logistic Regression¶

In [74]:
X_test = df_data1[cols_to_use1].values
In [75]:
print('Testing shapes:',X_test.shape)

Testing shapes: (20352, 135)

I have used the following code to predict probabilities of hospital readmissions for 20352 patients. I have used Logistic Regression to output these probabilities.

In [76]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.datasets.samples_generator import make_blobs
#Generating a 2d classification dataset 
X_train_tf, y_train = make_blobs(n_samples=100, centers=2, n_features=2, random_state=1)
#Fitting final Model
lr = LogisticRegression(solver='liblinear',random_state = 0)
lr.fit(X_train_tf, y_train)
#New instances from test set 
X_test, _ = make_blobs(n_samples=20352, centers=2, n_features=2, random_state=1)
#Predicting probabilities using predict_proba function 
probability = lr.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
#Displaying inputs and predicted probalities
for i in range(len(X_test)):
	print("X=%s, Predicted=%s" % (X_test[i], probability[i]))

VII. Interpretation of Results¶

After calculating predicted probabilities for each patient, it is important to interpret the results we have gotten. By setting the threshold probability at 0.90, I found that exactly 50% of the patients have more than a 90% chance of getting readmitted. This is a significantly strong chance of readmission and suggests that serious steps should be taken to reduce this high readmission rate. Reducing readmission rate will be able to significantly reduce healthcare costs while improving the quality of health care.

VIII. Next Steps¶

Diabetes is an epidemic which has serious economic and health consequences. Actions to avoid patient readmissions should start as soon as the patient is admitted to the hospital. Potential steps to reduce readmissions can be :

  1. Educating the patients through trained nurses and doctors.
  2. Better discharge instructions such as providing a Diabetes Discharge Kit and post-discharge support.
  3. Specialty care and better coordination of diabetes care facilities.
  4. Following up is extremely important for patients recently being discharged and details as to where and when to follow up should be communicated properly.
